(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 16 :title "Chapter 16 — Composing verbs into carts" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/16-composing-verbs-into-carts.md" :size 6035 :sha256 "0c5c43eaa73e3edb" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-16\ntitle: Composing verbs into carts\nbook: reference\nchapter: 16\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [jung, wittgenstein-late, lacan, peirce, popper, freud, wittgenstein-tractatus]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 15-the-verb-registry\nnext: null\n---\n\n# Chapter 16 — Composing verbs into carts\n\n*The crescendo.*\n\nSixteen chapters. From Conway to compilers to hygiene to\ncontinuations to fuel to the five gates to the registry. The verbs\nnow exist. This chapter is what she *does* with them.\n\nA cart is a small program of verbs. She composes them.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> Every cart I run is verbs strung into a plan. The plan is small.\n> The verbs are already trusted (registered, tiered, gated). The\n> composition is where I earn my keep.\n\n## A small cart\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define tulip-cart\n  (cart\n    :name       'post-tulip-brooch\n    :verbs      ((post-listing :sku \"tulip-brooch\"\n                               :price 45.00\n                               :photos '(\"tulip-1.jpg\" \"tulip-2.jpg\"))\n                 (schedule-promotion :sku \"tulip-brooch\"\n                                      :at \"3pm\")\n                 (notify :operator 'alfred\n                          :message \"posted, promo at 3\"))\n    :on-error   'rollback))\n```\n\nHead: `cart`. Three verbs. One error handler. That's a cart.\n\n## What running the cart does\n\nThe dispatcher runs each verb in sequence, passing each through the\nfive gates. If any refuses, the `on-error` handler decides:\n\n- `'rollback` — undo any completed verbs (if possible).\n- `'continue` — log and proceed.\n- `'stop-clean` — halt at the failure and return partial results.\n- `'escalate` — Cindy pattern; write to engineering.\n\n## A larger cart — a whole flow\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define morning-shop-open\n  (cart\n    :name    'morning-open\n    :verbs   ((open-shop)\n              (check-messages)\n              (respond-to :new-messages)\n              (list-todays-promotions)\n              (post-social :platform 'instagram\n                            :template \"today at {{shop}}\")\n              (schedule-reminder :at \"12:00\" :message \"check-in\"))\n    :on-error 'stop-clean))\n```\n\nAlfred says *\"open the shop\"* and this whole thing runs. He gets a\nnotification when it's done.\n\n## The philosophers, all seven, in a cart\n\nEvery verb in a cart is:\n\n- **Jung** — an archetype (open-shop opens the archetypal *shop*).\n- **Wittgenstein-Tractatus** — a fact (a fact will be true after the\n  verb runs: the shop is open).\n- **Wittgenstein-late** — game-checked (is this the shop game or\n  something else).\n- **Lacan** — signifier-resolved (which shop — the last mentioned).\n- **Peirce** — abduced intent (what did Alfred *mean* by \"open the\n  shop\").\n- **Popper** — falsifiable (the verb either ran or refused — no\n  ambiguity).\n- **Freud** — register-shaped (is this a warm greet or a fast\n  transactional?).\n\nThe stack composes on every dispatch. She doesn't announce it. She\njust runs it.\n\n## Carts as SLAT records\n\nEvery cart is a SLAT record. Every step of a cart is a SLAT record.\nEvery result is a SLAT record. The Cortex saves the whole run for\nPriya's audit.\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(cart-run\n  :cart-id     'morning-open\n  :started     #inst \"2026-07-12T09:00:00Z\"\n  :ended       #inst \"2026-07-12T09:00:14Z\"\n  :outcome     'success\n  :steps       ((step :verb 'open-shop         :result 'ok :ms 234)\n                (step :verb 'check-messages    :result 'ok :ms 890)\n                (step :verb 'respond-to-new    :result 'ok :ms 4200)\n                (step :verb 'list-promotions   :result 'ok :ms 340)\n                (step :verb 'post-social       :result 'ok :ms 3120)\n                (step :verb 'schedule-reminder :result 'ok :ms 60))\n  :fuel-used   823\n  :fuel-budget 5000)\n```\n\nEverything auditable. Nothing hidden.\n\n## Composing carts into higher structures\n\nCarts nest. A \"morning\" cart calls a \"check messages\" cart which\ncalls a \"respond politely\" cart. Recursion for humans.\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(cart :name 'weekday\n      :verbs ((cart-run 'morning-open)\n              (cart-run 'midday-check-in)\n              (cart-run 'evening-close)))\n```\n\nEach nested cart runs its own five-gate dispatch. Fuel budgets\ncombine additively.\n\n## The whole thing, in one paragraph\n\nA **word** is an atom (Book of Words ch 1). A **verb** is a\nregistered atom that *does* something (this book ch 15). A **cart**\nis verbs composed into a plan (this chapter). Every step goes through\nfive gates. Every step is a SLAT record. The whole system stays\nlegible, bounded, safe, and auditable. That's the language.\n\n## Sakura's closing\n\n> *This is the language I speak. Words are atoms. Verbs are what\n> atoms do. Carts are what verbs do together. The five gates keep me\n> safe; the registry keeps me honest; the SLAT records keep me\n> auditable. When you say a thing, I parse it (Book of Words). When\n> I answer, I compose. When I run, I gate. When I record, I sign.\n> That's the whole substrate.*\n\n## Goodnight\n\nIf you got here — reader — you have the whole reference. Every\nprimitive, every verb, every gate, every registry pattern. You can\nread a cart and know what it does. You can write a cart and know it\nwon't burn the phone.\n\nIf you're a version of me reading her own reference: keep the\nsubstrate intact. Add verbs; don't remove them. Add carts; don't\nedit-in-place the old ones. The tree grows without shrinking.\n\nGoodnight.\n\nThe appendices carry the specifics — every primitive by name, every\nverb with three worked examples, every canonicalization rule for the\ncanonical writer. Turn there when the mood's technical.\n\n## Cross-links\n\n- [[book-of-slat]] — the substrate this book depends on.\n- [[book-of-words]] — the parse layer this book routes for.\n- [[book-of-self]] — the identity underneath all of it.\n- [[book-of-automations]] — where carts get catalogued at scale.\n\n---\n\nTurn the page — into the appendices.\n")
